Exchange of property at divorce – Land and livestock are exchanged in the process of divorce between mutually feuding families to be held by the adult woman(s) of the family, often in the short term.

Divorce is no-alternative: Women traditionally see divorce as a possibility irrespective of whether they accept or consider the cause of divorce. Most often, divorce is not seen as a satisfactory solution to marital discord, especially problems arising from in-laws. Rather, divorce is a ‘necessary evil’, and extremely high rates exist as a result of this pragmatic attitude.

Recommendations to improve women’s access to divorce through land and livestock in the CAR and to mitigate the negative impacts of gender inequitable land and livestock access on women faced with divorce includes the following:

Governments and donor agencies should ensure that women are formally and legally represented through their Governments and – in line with the GALS approach – their participation is ensured at all decision levels of land and livestock governance processes as well as services, including micro-finance, natural resource management, and related legal and justice reforms.

Legal frameworks related to land and livestock generally should be reviewed.
